  "prompt": "What are the process and steps for the bridging course in Australia for nurses?",
  "response": "The bridging course for overseas-trained nurses in Australia is designed to help international nurses meet the registration standards set by the Nursing and Midwifery Board of Australia (NMBA). Here are the general steps and process:\n\n1. Initial Assessment\n- Verify your nursing qualifications\n- Submit educational credentials\n- Undergo English language proficiency test (IELTS or OET)\n\n2. Skills Assessment\n- Apply to the Australian Nursing and Midwifery Accreditation Council (ANMAC)\n- Have your nursing qualifications assessed\n- Provide proof of professional experience\n- Submit required documentation\n\n3. Bridging Program\nTypical components include:\n- Theoretical coursework\n- Clinical practice placement\n- Australian healthcare system orientation\n- Professional nursing practice modules\n- Cultural competency training\n\n4. Registration Requirements\n- Complete bridging course successfully\n- Obtain provisional registration\n- Pass Australian nursing practice standards\n- Complete background checks\n\n5. Final Registration\n- Apply to the Nursing and Midwifery Board of Australia\n- Pay registration fees\n- Provide all necessary documentation\n\nNote: Specific requirements can vary slightly between states and educational institutions.\n\nRecommended universities offering bridging courses include:\n- Charles Sturt University\n- Monash University\n- Australian Catholic University",
